Isn't it crazy how quickly our minds become accustomed to something? And then it changes and BAM! You do a double-take every time you see it?

That would be the pantry. I cleaned it last night (should have taken a before - we had groceries spilling out into the hallway for weeks), and now everytime I walk in there my little heart yells, "It's CLEEEEEEEEAN!!!" 🤣🤣

Finishing this space is getting to the top of our lists. With everything going crazy in the world today plus living in a small town where Costco is over an hour away, we knew we wanted a good food storage space. 

At the last minute (like after our inspection, ahem) I added plugs on that left side so we can put in a counter and make a little butler's pantry area. Sooooo excited. We'll have cabinets on the left, and built-in shelves similar to the ones in the back down the entire right side. 

#ownerbuild #pantry #cabinets #foodstorage

We sat and stared at the Costco fake Christmas tree yesterday for like 30 minutes. 

"Do you think it's time? None of the kids want to go out."

"Maybe we should. It would be easier. It's symmetrical. It's full. The lights are pretty."

So we loaded it on the cart, dragged it all around the store, paid for it, and after snagging a chicken bake for dinner we eyed the box in sad forlorness for another 15 minutes while we ate.

"We should just return it," I said.

Sam immediately perked up. "Really?!"

On our way out, we stopped by the return desk and left them the box.

Then today we traipsed around the forest in utter bliss for over an hour until we found this beauty to take home. 

We have issues. 🤣

But at least we have a fresh, beautiful tree to celebrate our first Christmas in the house we built.

#christmastree #foresttree #ownerbuilder #ownerbuild #lifeoneasystreet

We had a few friends swing by the house this week. They walked down our east side fence, right in front of our living room windows, and casually tromped across the neighboring lot before finding a snack they were interested in munching. 

Phew. Our trees are safe for now. 🌲
Love the way our new house is shaping up for Christmas. It makes me so happy to decorate and craft again! 🥰
Merry Christmas from our family to yours!

Say hello to Renarin. 

The fish experiment has been going mostly well. We've had our fish for months now and they all seemed fat and happy. And alive. Which is a plus. 

When we left the weekend before last something happened to our betta, Adolin, and when we got home we could tell he was really sick. I thought maybe he had just eaten too much, the pet shop thought he might have a tumor. Either way he passed on this week to much sadness. The tank feels a lot more empty without him.

Today we picked up his brother! I guess we'll see how this guy copes in an already established tank. 🤞

I don't usually subscribe to the idea of picking a word for the year, but as I was thinking about it this morning, one actually came to mind:

Celebrate. 🎉

This is a big year in numbers for us. 
▪️Cara turns 13 in May.
▪️I turn 40 in June.
▪️Andrew turns 16 in August.
▪️Our 20th anniversary is in August.
▪️Rachel turns 18 in Sept.

We will finish this HUGE house building project we started over 2 years ago.

Along with the accomplishments by calendar date comes immense gratitude for the opportunities we've been given, our family, the time we've spent cultivating those relationships, the incredible community we have become a part of, and this beautiful valley we are privileged to call home. 

I think that's cause for celebration, don't you?

Calling all RAD lady mountain biking shredders! Registration for @ladiesallride camps for 2023 opens TODAY!

If you have ever wanted to learn mountain bike skills in an uplifting, no pressure, non judgemental environment then pick the closest camp and SIGN UP. 

Never mountain biked before? Awesome. Want to learn new skills? This is the place. Time to take it to the next level? Bring it on.

I have spent 3 years volunteering, assisting, coaching, and being coached by this amazing organization and I love it. Its one of the highlights of my summer for sure. The support, fun, and experience is absolutely worth the time and effort to get there. 

Let's gooooooo!!!
#ladiesallride #mountainbike #womenonbikes #livcycling

THS Prom 2023!

Between choir, the musical, and church I interact with this group of kids quite frequently and they are so much fun. I love that they asked me to take photos again (although I could do without SNOW, c'mon weather), and the boys even picked out a spot with the most ah-mazing evening light. 🥰

I know I gripe a lot about how hard it is to parent teenagers, but dang it. They are also stinkin' amazing.

Sometimes I wonder how we had time to build a house. Where did all of those hours come from? With how busy we have been over the last 4 months I can't fathom how we ever made that work. 🤔

My only conclusion is that we had an amazing amount of heavenly help. 

Also, less kid activities, school, emotional struggles, and work. 

BUT, this week the sun came out both physically and mentally. 🤣 The snow is almost gone and we are feeling the desire to get stuff done, so we decided to do a thing. We looked at our list of remaining projects and determined that shelves in the mechanical room was the pick me up we needed to get back into project mode. 

Going from zero to done in one day and having a bit more organization is so satisfying. 

#homebuild #ownerbuild #organization #shelving #buildingahouse

"Now THAT feels more like home." - Andrew

I totally cracked up when I found out he said that after we put the scaffolding back up. 🤣 

We just have this one little section of siding to finish, which honestly feels like an old friend at this point. Hoping to knock it out around spring thunderstorms this weekend so we can take the scaffolding back to my father in law in Oregon. 

And then it's going to feel SO good to be DONE with that. 🎉🥳

Let's gooooo!!!

#ownerbuilder #ownerbuild #builtnotbought #siding #tongueandgroovepanelling

Super grateful for all the people in my life that make everything worthwhile. Cheers to 40! 🥳🧁🥰

When I chose to leave NICA this year I thought long and hard if I wanted to coach anything, OR if I even still liked my bike and wanted to ride at all. 

Then, my very first ride of the season (totally out of shape and puffing pretty hard), my friend and I ran into two other people on a local trail. Those two women were wearing @ladiesallride socks, commented on mine, and an enthusiastic commentary on the Grand Targhee skills camp ensued. 

Just watching their faces light up while remembering their experience felt like a sign - yes! I did still want to be part of this amazing effort to get #morewomenonbikes. Ladies All Ride is a family and everyone is invited. 

I had the opportunity to assist an amazing head coach up at @bigskyresort last weekend and once again, these women blew my mind.

Definitely sticking around. 😍🥰

Alaska is state #50 for us! This was the last one on our list and it took a few years post full time travel to get here, but we made it! First stop is Sitka, where we are mostly just wandering around on our own. 😍

It felt so good to be back behind the camera shooting portraits last night!

Pre-travel I was a wedding/family lifestyle/newborn photographer in Utah. It's been long enough that my kids don't really remember that piece of my life.

After a decade off and some soul searching, we decided it was time to dust the camera off and relaunch my photo business @picturememine. 

Best place to start? High school seniors!! These are new for me, but since our kids are right in the thick of it I'm excited to add these to my wheelhouse.

Sam tagged along as my lighting assistant, and we went to scope locations, run through the new equipment (it's amazing what the industry can produce in 10 years!) and see if I could get back in the groove. 

Mission accomplished. ✅ 

Also, our daughter is freaking gorgeous. I can't believe she'll be a senior next year. Girl, I can't wait to see what you do with the rest of your life. 🥰

Our spaces in the house are always evolving. I know it's true of every other place I've lived, but somehow I thought when we built our own house it would be different? Apparently not. 

We needed a place for the kids to practice their music that wasn't in the main room. Since I'm the only one regularly using the workout room (and I don't even use the treadmill lately) we transformed this corner into a little music space. 

Turns out concrete floors echo pretty extensively so we bought these felt wall decorations to help minimize the echo and also keep the sound in the room and not the whole house. So far we love it!

Can I start a GoFundMe for camera gear? Is that allowed?  I've rented the #CanonR6MarkII for the next week (and have like 7 shoots lined up!) And I already love it. 

Shooting with a @canonusa body + lens just really feels like coming home. It even *smells* like a Canon. I kid you not. 😂

The camera industry has made amazing strides in the last decade. I love the jump to mirrorless in the big brands even if the lens mount is different.  Good thing I sold my gazillion dollars of equipment off a long time ago to travel? Makes switching easier. 😬🤷‍♀️🤦‍♀️

Also, it's definitely fall. 😍🍂

Still have a long way to go until we are finished but this is happiness. 🥰

"The idea that every single thing we do must tie into the next rather than drawing to a close that is appropriate, necessary, and warranted is really damaging to our sense of self and can be an impediment to our progress." -@nicolewalters 

Since we stopped traveling full time in 2018, I've still had one foot out the door. That's hard for me to admit, but it's true. It has held me back. There's been a lot of "what ifs" and "maybe we could's." We've joked for quite a while now about my mid-life crisis and how I have felt lost. Not confident in my old identity, but unsure of who I really wanted to be.

When I read this quote in Nicole Walter's book "Nothing is Missing" last night I felt an overwhelming sense of peace. I'm okay to sell our house on wheels and let that chapter of our lives come to a close. It's okay to mourn the end of a season and acknowledge everything we learned, the growth obtained, and the friendships made. But it's also healthy to occasionally reinvent ourselves and see how far we can go.

As I recently started the journey of re-launching, re-branding, and then overhauling my photography business into something extraordinary, I felt myself coming alive again. I desperately love my job - with an intensity and excitement I haven't felt in a long time. This is going to be the start of an amazing new season.

 My passion is beautifully finished, heirloom quality wall art. I've had this photo in a smaller, unframed print in our Airstream, but ordered a larger, metal framed version for our new house - a bit of the old with the new.

I couldn't be more grateful to @kylenecleaver for photographing our family on our journey more than a decade ago. I will treasure these forever. ♥️

This is HUGE. We've been in our house for over a year and last night was the first time we were able to park a car in the garage. 🥳

We found a tenant for our condo and moved everything over from that garage last month (it's basically been our storage unit) and dumped it in an unceremonious mess. I finally put on my big girl pants yesterday and went through it all. We have a huge pile to donate, a pile to sell, threw away a lot and then reorganized into the bins on the back shelves. 

We are also going to get some of my father in law's tools back to him as his shop is coming along quite nicely - which will clear up more space. 

We still have kitchen cabinets to make, so we'll back the car out and pull out the table saw (also have a paint booth along that right side) so it'll be hit and miss, but FOR RIGHT NOW we have the Subaru in the garage. 

This means school drop off in the mornings will be much less freezing - which makes me extremely excited.

Celebrating the little wins along the way because owner-building a house is a forever long process. 😂😂

Okay, maybe I am a *little* excited for some winter wonderland photo sessions.

Where are you spending the holiday weekend this year? Home or traveling?

As retired full-time travelers, we've had our share of adventurous Thanksgiving celebrations. One of my favorites was to pack up our own version of a Mountain House Thanksgiving meal (stuffing, freeze-dried chicken, cranberries, and gravy!) and take our 3 young kids backpacking. 

These are two of my favorite memories: FDR State Park, GA (2015), and Channel Islands National Park, CA (2016).

For the first time in quite a while, we will be celebrating at home in Idaho with some close friends. It's already been a super relaxing, yet productive weekend and we can't wait for Sam to smoke a turkey on the Traegar. Already drooling.

I love it when high school seniors have amazing ideas! My daughter came to me a few weeks ago with some music photos she loved so we set to work recreating a few of them. 

I'd forgotten how much I love having a studio space! Tiny, and currently one seamless gray backdrop, but turns out there's a lot of fun things we can do with lights. 😍

Would you consider studio portraits?

Is anyone else a planner? Loves to have a vision of the entire year?? 🙋‍♀️ Last year I came up with a word of the year, and then promptly felt like all of 2023 went in the OPPOSITE direction. Looking back, I can still see how it would apply, and realize there is so much GAIN even though I distinctly still feel the GAP of where I wanted to be by December.

Earlier this week I was encouraged by my mentor to create a vision board for 2024 - really project out what I wanted this year to look like. 

It was rather therapeutic! I tried to keep it small - we had such a busy summer that I felt we didn't do anything locally and both Sam and I are dying to get up backpacking in the Tetons again. Add some fitness (probably should have put pickleball on there!), some new camera gear and voila!
